<div class="row">
<h3>How do you envision your future and more generally the future of young First Nations in Quebec and Canada?</h3>
<div class="col-xs-12">
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/GZU0YFaTraw" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p> «I am going to pursue a course in specialised education, because I would like to work for a school board for people with intellectual and physical disabilities.
Afterwards I would like to build my own house in Odanak. That way, I will be able to stay close to my parents. I don’t like being far from them. Also, there are good work opportunities here. For sure, it would be ideal if I could work in my community here, it is really one of my goals because I love Odanak.»
</br></br>(...)</br></br>«For Odanak, I am not quite certain what will happen, but for sure we are less and less in the community, we are about 2500 to 3000 abenakis staying, who were registered in 2012. Otherwise, I can’t say what will happen, I hope there will be a glorious future for First Nations, that more youths will go to school, that they won’t drop out of school.»
</br></br>(...)</br></br>«If we never take care of the people within the communities, and if we don’t care for the community itself by working for it, by living inside/there, if we all go away… For sure, the communities won’t persist through time. So, I personally find it a shame. We should push ourselves to reach out… You know I am abenakis but I am willing to help other First Nations too. The problems are not only here, there are really everywhere in the communities.»
</div></div>

<div class="row">
<h3>What do you see as the challenges faced by indigenous youths?</h3>
<div class="col-xs-6">
  <img src="/pictures/bubbles/raph.png" alt="" height="298" width="273">
